reviewerName: Fabulinus "To err is human. To forgive for no...
reviewText: Wow, did I love this movie!  It was cute, had a great and well known cast and the dialog was very good.  Another major plus is that it didn't have the usual "buffoonery" that many predominately Black films have.  There's been quite the resurgence of films with predominately Black casts that have surfaced showing Black Americans in a horrible light:  excessively silly, ridiculously exaggerated and/or amoral characters, and the old style `shuckin' and `jivin' behavior that I thought had been put to permanent rest pre 1950.  This film showed a Black American family that still had dysfunction, but not the excessively exaggerated and broken types of dysfunction.  Furthermore, the movie showed what I like to call normalcy (yes, we do have it) in Black familial dynamics that can be light and that deal with universal human concepts.Super cute movie that I cannot say enough good things about.  Thank you, Hollywood.  You knocked it out of the park with this one!

reviewText: We rented it on redbox first as we do now with all movies because you just don't know what to trust these days when it comes to films, music or any entertainment for that matter...so much talentless crap out there but Peeples wasn't a disappointment!I'll admit some moments could've been funnier but the moments that were funny were really funny. The movie is about a girl(Kerry Washington,Ray/Scandal) who's boyfriend shows up to her parents Hamptons home with unannounced with intentions of asking her to marry him. Upon his arrival he's quickly and awkwardly introduced to the Peeples, a family who puts up a front of being pristine and perfect but in actuality they're dysfunctional and don't really know each other that well. The father-a prominent judge who's stiff and proper with his family but disappears each night to frolic the beach in the buff with a female neighbor, the mother- a recovering alcoholic and former disco star, the brother- a cleptomaniac who aspires to be a rockstar to shed his geek rep, the sister- a gorgeous closet lesbian, and the main character who has a secretof her own.  (The whole cast is actors/actresses that are some of the best at what they do. Not sure why so many negative reviews, seems like one person gave a bad review and everyone else jumped on the band wagon. If you're expecting Ted or Hangover type humor, it's not here because this isn't that kind of movie and Tyler Perry didn't actually write this so there's no inconsistent drama either...Thank God! Bottom line...Peeples churned out enough laughs to pick a depressed person up on "one of those days" so it passed the test. I would watch it again!
summary: Goes in the would watch it again category

reviewText: If you liked Meet the Parents, this movie is similar.  My husband and I enjoyed it and laughed several times.  I miss David Allen Grier and was happy to see him in a comedy.  It's basically about a daughter afraid to let her father rip apart the man in her life.  The age old question is can a man ever be good enough for your father?  Grier (Judge Peeples) is a serious character playing the role of a wealthy Federal Judge.  Craig Robinson (the boyfriend) is a talented kids kouncelor (with a K since he isn't licensed).  Basically you follow a sequence of events where the judge and his family is "supposed" to be perfect but end up being a normal family with issues like everyone else.  I enjoyed the movie and I am a christian.  I saw several christans who reviewed this movie and bashed it because of a gay couple.  Well that's life.  It's not perfect.  I am a christian but I will not stop loving my child if she comes out as gay.  The movie doesn't promote it, it is sharing the fact that the family isn't "perfect".  Basically if you want a few laughs, rent it.  It's a comedy, don't take movies so seriously they are for entertainment purpose only.  We watched it several times.  It's honestly a cute comedy.  I liked it enough to give it 4 stars too.

reviewText: If I had the option, I would have given this mosh of a movie two and a half stars rather than three. Granted, it's a comedy but I expect my movie comedies to be funny, plus have a somewhat plausible plot... this movie didn't quite make it there for me. Plot: a thirty something, attractive, sophisticated New York female lawyer, is dating a seemingly likable guy who works with children... I'm not sure what his actual job title is though. An odd couple for sure. She is reluctant to introduce him to her parents (mind you, she is well into her thirties!), so he decides to go uninvited to her parent's Hampton's home, intent on proposing marriage. Who does that? After a series of mishaps and silly (not funny) situations, he uncovers quirks about her not-so-perfect family members. As expected, it all works out in the end. As I watched, I wondered how such an assemblage of talented actors got sucked into such a silly movie. The cast included cameos from veteran actors Diahann Carroll and Melvin Van Peebles. In the credits, it became clear... Tyler Perry was involved! However, so was Charles S. Dutton whose past works are usually note worthy. Overall, I'd say if you don't care much about plausibility in plots, and are just looking for escapism with an all star cast, then this might do it for you. Otherwise, it was just ok.
Title: Tyler Perry: Peeples Digital

reviewText: A guy visits his girlfriend's family, for the purpose of proposing marriage. He finds that he has trouble fitting in, and has a particular problem receiving the blessing of the father. The situations he finds himself in are at times funny, with the family members, who all have their idiosyncrasies, proving to be fodder for laughs. This is not the cleverest movie of the year, but it does have its moments. It is certainly not Bridesmaids, but Peeples does have some good comedy in it, maybe just enough to get a slight recommendation.
Title: Tyler Perry: Peeples Digital

reviewText: I honestly started watching this movie because I was bored and had some free time, but even though it was fairly formulaic in the idea, the characters and the actors portraying them were so good, the movie was really enjoyable.  The movie is just plain funny, without trying for a bunch of sophomoric jokes (which I thought it would be full of, based upon the storyline provided with it).  Instead, it was funny because the writing was good and the situations were ridiculous, without being downright silly.  Well, maybe some were silly, but the cast had me so invested in the characters, the situations didn't seem silly at all.  So, well done.  A very funny movie.
Title: Tyler Perry: Peeples Digital

reviewText: The plot is simple and quite used before. The family is eccentric and a bit out-there, but still comes around like a real family would in the movie. reviewText: If nothing else Tyler Perry the producer knows how to make incredibly obvious "this small detail makes it different from my other movie" moments, like a lesbian sister  so that you think you're watching something new. In reality the crew he uses here is not talking about anything of significance and everything is so cute here that it needs better comedic timing. The individual actors have that timing, but in the hands of boring direction and lighting it just comes off as something to get in the dollar bin at your local store. Craig Robinson and Kerry Washington who are great separately have zero chemistry or beleivability as a couple, and actually would have been way more believable as some kind of platonic friends.
summary: Cutesy modern black dilemas with no soul at all

reviewerName: The Movie Guy "Movies from A to Z"
reviewText: Wade Walker (Craig Robinson) lives with Grace Peeples (Kerry Washington). He relates to children through music and wants to be a counselor. She is a lawyer at the UN and her family is referred to as the "chocolate Kennedys." Wade's plans to propose to Grace are interrupted by her desire to spend the weekend with her family, who he has never met. Urged by a friend (Malcolm Barrett), Wade crashes the family get together with formulaic results.As it turns out the family has all sorts of issues and secrets which they hide from their father, Judge Virgil Peeples (David Alan Grier). Wade spends his time having an uncomfortable weekend filled with faux paus as he tries to help. The film includes Peeple/people and cheap Moby Dick humor.For those who like Tyler Perry type comedies, this one fits the bill, but comes off a little stale. It does have some good scenes which made me smile. The film needed to have one more episode to develop Wade's character before he meets the family, then have him either draw from his talents, or better yet, have to do just the opposite to resolve issues with her family. It attempts, but fails to do that effectively, missing the key ingredient of the formula success.Parental Guide: No f-bombs, sex, or nudity. Sexual talk, spanking, role play, implied sex.
Title: Tyler Perry: Peeples Digital

reviewText: "We're not the chocolate Kennedys." Wade Walker (Robinson) is in love with Grace Peeples (Washington) and is getting ready to propose. Grace leaves for the weekend to visit her family without inviting Wade. After talking to his brother Wade gets up the courage to surprise her at her family's cabin. When he shows up things don't go as planned and he begins to question if this is a family he wants to be a part of. First off I have to say I'm not racist. That said if Tyler Perry's name is on a movie I tend to avoid it. Even though this is just a "Tyler Perry Presents" it was enough to lower my expectations. I'm not sure if it was the low expectations or not but I ended up really enjoying this and laughing the whole way through. Robinson is very funny and David Allen Grier has some really funny scenes in this. It's a good thing the comedy was there though because the movie is so generic and overdone that the laughs are the only thing that made it interesting. After 5 minutes you can pretty much tell exactly what is going to happen. Overall, a funny movie that was much, much better then I was expecting. I surprisingly give it a B+.
summary: A movie that is so unoriginal & generic that if not for Robinson & the comedy it would be hard to watch. I did laugh alot. B+
Title: Tyler Perry: Peeples Digital
